title: collinear: How It Works
text: Pairwise correlation commonly used detect reduce multicollinearity identifying pairs predictors highly correlated . function cor_select() builds upon concept improves integrating categorical predictors correlation analysis, implementing automated selection algorithm designed preserve important predictors. function performs following steps: Computes pairwise correlation matrix using methods able integrate categorical predictors. Applies forward stepwise multicollinearity filtering select predictors certain correlation threshold. Pairwise Correlation Matrix Pairwise correlations computed cor_df(). Notice original sign correlation kept output, correlation column arranged using absolute values instead. three possible cases handle building correlation matrix: Numeric vs numeric (cor_numeric_vs_numeric()): Computes R-squared predictors. Numeric vs categorical (cor_numeric_vs_categorical()): categorical predictor target-encoded numeric, R-squared computed. Categorical vs categorical (cor_categorical_vs_categorical()): Computes Cramer’s V predictors. Please, taken mind comparing Cramer’s V R-squared suboptimal solution, always preferable target-encode categorical predictors pairwise correlation analysis. function cor_matrix() removes correlation sign rearranges pairwise correlations data frame correlation matrix. first 10 rows columns correlation matrix shown . Multicollinearity Filtering forward stepwise multicollinearity filtering implemented cor_select() works follows: Order pairwise correlation matrix match preference_order. Add first first predictor preference_order vector selected. every predictor: get maximum correlation predictors selected. lower max_cor, add selected, ignore otherwise. Move next predictor tested. None predictors selected absolute pairwise correlation others higher defined threshold.
code: df_cor <- collinear::cor_df(   df = vi,   predictors = vi_predictors ) x <- collinear::cor_numeric_vs_numeric(   df = vi,   predictors = c(     "temperature_mean", #numeric     "temperature_max"   #numeric   ) ) x <- collinear::cor_numeric_vs_categorical(   df = vi,   predictors = c(     "temperature_mean", #numeric     "soil_type"         #categorical   ) ) x <- collinear::cor_categorical_vs_categorical(   df = vi,   predictors = c(     "koppen_zone",      #categorical     "soil_type"         #categorical   ) ) m <- collinear::cor_matrix(   df = df_cor ) #preference order from a previous example preference_order <- preference_list$vi_numeric$predictor  #correlation threshold max_cor <- 0.5  #reorder pairwise correlation matrix m <- m[   preference_order,   preference_order ]  #set diagonals to zero diag(m) <- 0  #initialize required vectors selected <- preference_order[1] candidates <- preference_order[-1]  #iterate over candidates for(candidate in candidates){      #apply selection criteria   if(max(m[selected, candidate]) <= max_cor){          selected <- c(       selected,       candidate     )        }    }  selected #>  [1] "rainfall_mean"   "swi_min"         "country_gdp"     "swi_range"       #>  [5] "temperature_min" "humidity_range"  "topo_diversity"  "soil_clay"       #>  [9] "topo_elevation"  "country_income"  "soil_silt" df_cor <- collinear::cor_df(   df = df,   predictors = selected )

title: Automated multicollinearity management — collinear
text: Automates multicollinearity management data frames numeric non-numeric predictors combining four methods: Target Encoding: numeric response provided encoding_method NULL, transforms categorical predictors (classes "character" "factor") numeric using response values reference. See target_encoding_lab() details. Preference Order: response type provided via response, association response predictor computed appropriate function (see preference_order() f_auto()), predictors ranked higher lower association. rank used preserve important predictors multicollinearity filtering. Pairwise Correlation Filtering: Automated multicollinearity filtering via pairwise correlation. Correlations numeric categoricals  predictors computed target-encoding categorical predictor, correlations categoricals computed via Cramer's V. See cor_select(), cor_df(), cor_cramer_v() details. VIF filtering: Automated algorithm identify remove numeric predictors linear combinations predictors. See vif_select() vif_df(). Accepts parallelization setup via future::plan() progress bar via progressr::handlers() (see examples). Accepts character vector response variables input argument response. one response provided, output named list character.

text: functions take data frame two numeric continuous columns "x" (predictor) "y" (response), fit univariate model, return R-squared observations versus model predictions: f_r2_pearson(): Pearson's R-squared. f_r2_spearman(): Spearman's R-squared. f_r2_glm_gaussian(): Pearson's R-squared GLM model fitted stats::glm(), formula y ~ s(x) family stats::gaussian(link = "identity"). f_r2_glm_gaussian_poly2(): Pearson's R-squared GLM model fitted stats::glm(), formula y ~ stats::poly(x, degree = 2, raw = TRUE) family stats::gaussian(link = "identity"). f_r2_gam_gaussian(): Pearson's R-squared GAM model fitted mgcv::gam(), formula y ~ s(x) family stats::gaussian(link = "identity"). f_r2_rpart(): Pearson's R-squared Recursive Partition Tree fitted rpart::rpart() formula y ~ x. f_r2_rf(): Pearson's R-squared 100 trees Random Forest model fitted ranger::ranger() formula y ~ x.

title: Quantitative Variable Prioritization for Multicollinearity Filtering — preference_order
text: Ranks set predictors strength association response. Aims minimize loss important predictors multicollinearity filtering. strength association response predictor computed function f. f functions available : Numeric response vs numeric predictor: f_r2_pearson(): Pearson's R-squared. f_r2_spearman(): Spearman's R-squared. f_r2_glm_gaussian(): Pearson's R-squared response versus predictions Gaussian GLM. f_r2_glm_gaussian_poly2(): Gaussian GLM second degree polynomial. f_r2_gam_gaussian(): GAM model fitted mgcv::gam(). f_r2_rpart(): Recursive Partition Tree fitted rpart::rpart(). f_r2_rf(): Random Forest model fitted ranger::ranger(). Integer counts response vs. numeric predictor: f_r2_glm_poisson(): Pearson's R-squared Poisson GLM. f_r2_glm_poisson_poly2(): Poisson GLM second degree polynomial. f_r2_gam_poisson(): Poisson GAM. Binomial response (1 0) vs. numeric predictor: f_auc_glm_binomial(): AUC quasibinomial GLM weighted cases. f_auc_glm_binomial_poly2(): second degree polynomial. f_auc_gam_binomial(): Quasibinomial GAM weighted cases. f_auc_rpart(): Recursive Partition Tree weighted cases. f_auc_rf(): Random Forest model weighted cases. Categorical response (character factor) vs. categorical predictor: f_v(): Cramer's V two categorical variables. Categorical response vs. categorical numerical predictor: f_v_rf_categorical(): Cramer's V Random Forest model. name used function stored attribute "f_name" output data frame. can retrieved via attributes(df)$f_name Additionally, custom function accepting data frame columns "x" (predictor) "y" (response) returning numeric indicator association higher numbers indicate higher association work. function returns data frame column "predictor", predictor names ordered column "preference", result f. data frame, column "predictor" alone, can used inputs argument preference_order collinear(), cor_select(), vif_select(). Accepts parallelization setup via future::plan() progress bar via progressr::handlers() (see examples). Accepts character vector response variables input argument response. one response provided, output named list preference data frames.

title: Target Encoding Lab: Transform Categorical Variables to Numeric — target_encoding_lab
text: Target encoding involves replacing values categorical variables numeric ones derived "target variable", usually model's response. essence, target encoding works follows: 1. group cases belonging unique value categorical variable. 2. compute statistic target variable across group cases. 3. assign value statistic group. methods compute group statistic implemented : "mean" (implemented target_encoding_mean()): Encodes categorical values group means response. Variables encoded method identified suffix "__encoded_mean". method control overfitting implemented via argument smoothing. integer value argument indicates threshold number rows. Groups threshold encoded group mean, groups encoded weighted mean group's mean global mean. method named "mean smoothing" relevant literature. "rank" (implemented target_encoding_rank()): Returns rank group integer, 1 group lower mean response variable. Variables encoded method identified suffix "__encoded_rank". "loo" (implemented target_encoding_loo()): Known "leave-one-method" literature, encodes categorical value mean response variable across group cases. method controls overfitting better "mean". Variables encoded method identified suffix "__encoded_loo". Accepts parallelization setup via future::plan() progress bar via progressr::handlers() (see examples).

text: Now works combination categorical numeric responses predictors. Previously, numeric responses considered valid. Now issues warning predictors show suspiciously high association response. sensitivity test controlled new argument warn_limit. Parallelization setup now managed via future::plan(), progress bar available progressr::handlers().
